# Project Euler 13: Large Sum
# Work out the first ten digits of the sum of the 100 fifty-digit numbers
# below.
# Answer: 5537376230
#
# A LESSON IN LANGUAGE DESIGN, NOT JUST ALGORITHMS:
# BARE has exactly one numeric type, and it's a float — a deliberate
# simplification (see docs/language-spec.md, "one numeric type"). Floats
# are only exact up to about 15-16 digits; these numbers have 50. Add a
# few of them with plain "+" and you'd silently get a wrong answer with no
# error at all, which is worse than a crash.
#
# So this program does NOT use BARE's numbers for the numbers. It stores
# each 50-digit value as a STRING and adds two of them the way you did it
# in second grade: line up the digits, add from the right, carry the 1.
# add_big() below is that paper algorithm, coded up because the language
# won't do it for you.
#
# This is the point, not a workaround to feel bad about: BARE can still do
# real work here, at a real cost — more code, more places to get it wrong,
# and it only works because someone (you) reimplemented arithmetic by
# hand. A language with a real arbitrary-precision integer type makes this
# whole file disappear into a single "+". Feeling that gap is exactly why
# this teaching suite doesn't stop at BARE.

sub add_big(a, b)
    result = ""
    carry = 0
    i = len(a) - 1
    j = len(b) - 1
    while i >= 0 or j >= 0 or carry > 0
        digit_a = 0
        if i >= 0
            digit_a = num(a[i])
        end
        digit_b = 0
        if j >= 0
            digit_b = num(b[j])
        end
        total = digit_a + digit_b + carry
        digit = total % 10
        carry = (total - digit) / 10
        result = str(digit) + result
        i = i - 1
        j = j - 1
    end
    return result
end

